VWhat do we do about it?
p8
aVWell for most adults, it's a relatively mild disease \u2014
p9
aVa little fever, a little headache, joint pain, maybe a rash.
p10
aVIn fact, most people who get it don't even know they've had it.
p11
aVBut the more we find out about the Zika virus
p12
aVthe more terrifying it becomes.
p13
aVFor example, doctors have noticed an uptick
p14
aVof something called Guillain-Barré syndrome in recent outbreaks.
p15
aVIn Guillain-Barré, your immune system attacks your nerve cells
p16
aVit can partially or even totally paralyze you.
p17
aVFortunately, that's quite rare, and most people recover.
p18
aVBut if you're pregnant when you're infected
p19
aVyou're at risk of something terrible.
p20
aVIndeed, a child with a deformed head.
p21
aa(lp22
VHere's a normal baby.
p23
aVHere's that infant with what's called microcephaly.
p24
aVa brain in a head that's too small.
p25
aVAnd there's no known cure.
p26
aVIt was actually doctors in northeastern Brazil
p27
aVwho first noticed, just a year ago, after a Zika outbreak,
p28
aVthat there was a peak in the incidence of microcephaly.
p29
aVIt took medical doctors another year
p30
aVto be sure that it was caused by the Zika virus,
p31
aVbut they're now sure.
p32
aVAnd if you're a "bring on the evidence" type,
p33
aVcheck out this publication.
