aa(lp35
VSo where did it come from, and how did it get here?
p36
aVAnd it is here.
p37
aVLike many of our viruses, it came out of Africa,
p38
aVspecifically the Zika forest in Uganda.
p39
aVResearchers at the nearby Yellow Fever Research Institute
p40
aVidentified an unknown virus in a monkey in the Zika forest
p41
aVwhich is how it got its name.
p42
aVThe first human cases of Zika fever
p43
aVsurfaced a few years later in Uganda-Tanzania.
p44
aVThe virus then spread through West Africa
p45
aVand east through equatorial Asia \u2014 Pakistan, India, Malaysia, Indonesia.
p46
aVBut it was still mostly in monkeys and, of course, mosquitoes.
p47
aVIn fact in the 60 years between the time it was first identified in 1947 and 2007
p48
aVthere were only 13 reported cases of human Zika fever.
p49
aVAnd then something extraordinary happened on the tiny Micronesian Yap islands.
p50
aVThere was an outbreak that affected fully 75 percent of the population.
p51
aVHow did it get there? By air.
p52
aVToday we have two billion commercial airline passengers.
p53
aVAn infected passenger can board a plane, fly halfway around the world
p54
aVbefore developing symptoms \u2014 if they develop symptoms at all.
p55
aVThen when they land, the local mosquitoes begin to bite them and spread the fever.
p56
aVZika fever then next surfaced in 2013 in French Polynesia.
p57
aVBy December of that year, it was being transmitted locally by the mosquitoes.
p58
aVThat led to an explosive outbreak in which almost 30,000 people were affected.
p59
aVFrom there it radiated around the Pacific.
p60
aVThere were outbreaks in the Cook Islands, in New Caledonia,
p61
aVin Vanuatu, in the Solomon Islands
p62
aVand almost all the way around to the coast of South America and Easter Island.
p63
aVAnd then, in early 2015,
p64
aVthere was an upsurge of cases of a dengue-like syndrome
p65
aVin the city of Natal in northeastern Brazil.
p66
aVThe virus wasn't dengue, it was Zika, and it spread rapidly \u2014
p67
aVRecife down the coast, a big metropolitan center, soon became the epicenter.
p68
aVWell people have speculated that it was 2014 World Cup soccer fans
p69
aVthat brought the virus into the country.
p70
aVBut others have speculated that perhaps it was Pacific Islanders
p71
aVparticipating in championship canoe races
p72
aVthat were held in Rio that year that brought it in.
p73
aa(lp74
VWell today, this is only a year later.
p75
aVThe virus is being locally transmitted by mosquitoes
p76
aVvirtually throughout South America, Central America, Mexico
p77
aVand the Caribbean Islands
p78
aVUntil this year, the many thousands of cases
p79
aVthat have been diagnosed in the US were contracted elsewhere.
p80
aVBut as of this summer, it's being transmitted locally in Miami.
p81
aVIt's here.
