aVSo that leaves the mosquitoes, and here's how we control them now:
p100
aVspraying insecticides.
p101
aVThe protective gear is necessary because these are toxic chemicals
p102
aVthat kill people as well as bugs.
p103
aVAlthough it does take quite a lot more to kill a person than to kill a bug.
p104
aVThese are pictures from Brazil and Nicaragua.
p105
aVBut it looks the same in Miami, Florida.
p106
aVAnd we of course can spray insecticides from planes.
p107
aVLast summer, mosquito control officials in Dorchester County, South Carolina,
p108
aVauthorized spraying of Naled, an insecticide,
p109
aVearly one morning, as recommended by the manufacturer.
p110
aVLater that day, a beekeeper told reporters
p111
aVthat her bee yard looked like it had been nuked.
p112
aVOops.
p113
aVBees are the good guys.
p114
aVThe citizens of Florida protested, but spraying continued.
p115
aVUnfortunately, so did the increase in the number of Zika fever cases.
p116
aVThat's because insecticides aren't very effective.
